Birthplace of Tirthankar Lord Mahavira

Vasokund (Kundpur), Vaishali, Bihar

🏛️ पवित्र धरोहर देखें — Explore Heritage
✦

About Lord Mahavira

The 24th Tirthankar — A Light of Non-Violence, Non-Absolutism & Non-Possessiveness

Birth & Early Life

Vaishali is a great pilgrimage where Lord Mahavira was born. Here, in the palace, King Siddhartha and Queen Trishala lived and ruled religiously, peacefully & judiciously. Vardhaman was the name given to the prince born to Queen Trishala.

At the age of 30, he left his royal palace for his own emancipation and that of Mankind. After hard austere Tapasya of 12 years, he attained enlightenment and pure, complete knowledge by which he was called 'Sarwagya' and 'Kewaljnani' (omniscient).

Symbol & Identity

Symbol: Lion (Singh) — The Ashoka Pillar at Kolhua bears a Lion, which is also the symbol of Lord Mahavira.

Birth Date: Chaitra Shukla Trayodashi, under Uttara Phalguni Nakshatra

Parents: King Siddhartha & Queen Trishala (Priyakarini)

Birthplace: Kundpur (Vasokund), Vaishali, Videha

Jivant Swami — The Living Statue

When Prince Vardhman was ready to go for Deeksha in the forests, his mother Queen Trishala said to King Siddhartha: "Oh Lord! When Vardhman will leave us, whose face will I see everyday?" Then King Siddhartha requested that his statue be made.

Prince Vardhman thought that if He is permitted to leave just on the condition of his statue being made, it is a good deal. He called a statue maker and this statue was created. It is called 'Jivant Swami' and is available at the Museum in Vadodara. A similar statue is kept in the 'Rajkumar Vardhman Bhawan' at Vaishali.

"The first living statue (Jivant Pratima) of Rajkumar Vardhman was installed for the first time in Vaishali."

Philosophy & Principles

Ahimsa (Non-Violence), Anekant (Non-Absolutism), Aparigraha (Non-Possessiveness) — these rays of light from Tirthankar Mahavira have enlightened the world.

"Jainism, more than any other creed, gives absolute religious independence and freedom to man. Nothing can intervene between the actions which we do and the fruits thereof."
— Outlines of Jainism by Jugmanderlal Jaini, p.344

"Vardhamana Mahavir, the 24th Tirthankara in a meditative posture" — as published in the calligraphed edition of the Constitution of India.

✦

Birthplace Confirmation

Kundagram = Vasokund — Proven by scriptures, archaeology, and modern scholarship

Hermann Jacobi & Sacred Books of the East

In the "Sacred Books of the East", Volumes 22 and 45, translated by Hermann Jacobi, one of the greatest authorities on Jainism, he states:

"The Jainas, both Swetambars and Digambaras, believe that Mahavira was the son of King Siddhartha of Kundapur or Kundagrama. Kundagrama is called in the Acharanga Sutra as Samnivesa, a term which the commentator interprets as denoting an encampment place of caravans or processions."

Mahavira was born in Kundagrama near Vaishali (Basarha in the Hajipur sub-division of Muzaffarpur district). Kundagrama is known as Vasokund these days.

Excavated Seals & Brahmi Inscriptions

During excavation at Vaishali (1903-04 by Dr. T. Bloch), archaeologists found 12-15 coins with engravings of Vaishali Kundpur:

  • Vaishali Nam Kunde — The seal of Kundapur of Vaishali
  • Vaishalyaddhisthanadhikaran
  • Vaishali Nam Kunde-Kumarmattyadhikaran(sya)

A special seal found in Brahmi script reads: "Vaishali Namakunde Kumaramatyadhikaran(sya)" — proving Prince Vardhman held the position of 'Kumaramatya' (Prime Minister).

Bihar Government Jain Circuit

The tourism department of Bihar Government published a book 'Jain Circuit' in the year 2003, in which Vasokund in Vaishali is officially mentioned as the birthplace of Lord Mahavir.

Ashoka Pillar — Lion — Mahavira's Symbol

After the Deekshoupwas, Lord Mahavir ate for the first time (Parna) at Koolgram (now known as Kolhua). There is a stone pillar with a Lion called the Ashok Stambh.

The symbol of Lord Mahavir is also a 'Lion'. His ancestors reigned here. This pillar was made by Vajjio & Lichhivi as a memorial to Vardhman Mahavir.

Golden Past — Archaeological Finds

Upon excavation at Raja Vishal ka Garh:

  • Two bulls recovered — symbols of religion, charity, prosperity
  • A gold ear-ornament (Kundal) found — belonged to King Chetak's family
  • Lord Mahavir adorned this ornament during his youth — hence the name Kundalpur

Holy Blessings — Mangal Ashirwad

Sacred blessings from revered Acharyas for the temple at the birthplace

Parampujya Shwetpicchhacharya Shri Vidyanandji Muniraj

(Born: 22 April 1925 — Devlokgaman: 22 September 2019)

"Lord Mahavira was born at Vasokund (Kundpur). My Holy blessings are there to build Vardhman's magnificent temple at Vasokund (Kundpur) in Vaishali. This should have been completed much earlier. It is my holy desire and feeling that this work is now completed without any obstacles."

आचार्य श्रीविद्यानन्दजी मुनिराज के निर्देशन व मार्गदर्शन में सम्पन्न अति महत्त्वपूर्ण कार्य

  4. बावनगजा स्थित चौरासी फुट उतंग भगवान् आदिनाथ की प्रतिमा का जीर्णोद्धार एवं महामस्तकाभिषेक
  5. श्रीमहावीरजी (राजस्थान) स्थित भगवान् महावीर की प्रतिमा का सहस्राब्दी समारोह एवं महामस्तकाभिषेक

Parampujya Aacharya Shri Vidyasagar Muniraj

"The construction work of a temple (Jinalaya) of Lord Mahavira at the Birth-Place of Lord Mahavira at Vasokund (Kundpur) in Vaishali is in progress. This temple at Vaishali shall become the model epicentre of spreading the Principles of Lord Mahavira. It is my Holy Blessing that it may lead to the welfare of all the creatures."

Parampujya Aacharya Shri Vardhman Sagar Muniraj

"I realized that the lifestyle of Lord Mahavira and his principles like Brotherhood, Non-Violence, Tolerance, Secularism, Celibacy, etc. are embedded in the hearts of the people of Vaishali. I Bless all the citizens of Vaishali who have preserved these principles of Vardhman Mahavira and the events related to His Birth in their local folk songs & melodies and also retained His Birth Place as Uncultivated land even more than 2600 years after His Birth."

Parampujya Aacharya Shri Shrutsagar Muniraj

"Tirthankar Mahavira is a pillar of light from where the Rays of Non-Violence, Anekant (Non-Absolutism), Aparigraha (Non-Possessiveness) have enlightened the world. I give my Holy Blessing for this superb temple (Jinalaya) at Bhagwan Mahavir Birth Place Vasokund, Vaishali where construction is going on."

Parampujya Aacharya Shri Vishudhsagar Muniraj

"From the study of the entire Jainagam texts and from the research of modern scholars, historians and archaeologists, it has been known that Lord Mahavir Swami was born in Videha Desh, Vaishali, Kundapur (Bharatvarshe Videha Kundapuram) of Bharat Kshetra. I have my blessings for the completion of the construction work of the grand Jinalaya at this historic birthplace."

Bhattarak Charukirti — Guidance

"Vardhman Mahavir knew very well that every work is inspired by someone, and hence it is important to make that person look forward for development. The knowledge given by Him (Lord Mahavir) about the perspective of an individual and the society/community is very essential. My Holy Blessings are there for early completion of the construction work of this beautiful temple in Vaishali."

Dr. Virendra D. Heggade — Guidance (Param Shiromani Sanrakshak)

"Lord Mahavira does not represent any particular community, religion or society but He is established as a pride and glory of the whole mankind. Lord Mahavira's immense kindness not only towards human beings but also for speechless creatures was invaluable. He abolished exploitation and stress in the world by means of Non-Violence, Non-Possessiveness and Non-Absolutism. My best wishes are there for the construction of this Grand Temple at the Birth Place of Lord Mahavira in Vasokund, Vaishali at fast pace."

Acharya Mahashraman (Terapanth) — 23 March 2017

Acharya Mahashraman along with his Sangh (76 Sadhus and Sadhvis) visited the Birthplace on 23 March 2017. He was welcomed by Digambar Jain Acharya Shri Geetalsagar ji and his Sangh. He expressed happiness and wished for this to become an international centre for Ahimsa and Anekantavad.

Historical Importance of Vaishali

The Mother of Democracy — Where 7,707 representatives governed a prosperous republic

The Cradle of Democracy

During the time of Prince Vardhman, 7,707 Members of Parliament used to administer the Government. The area of each legislative constituency was very large. Every MP was honoured ceremonially and while he enjoyed privileges, he did not claim any special powers. Every one was filled with feeling of equality and pride.

Rock Hill wrote in 'Life of Buddha' (p.62): Vaishali had 1,68,000 population, 8,000 palaces (each with a garden and pond), 7,000 golden domes, 14,000 silver domes, and 21,000 bronze domes.

Buddha & Vaishali

Vaishali was very dear to Buddha. As mentioned in 'Mahaparinivvanasutt', when Buddha last proceeded from Vaishali, he looked back several times and said to Ananda:

"Ananda, I am seeing Vaishali for the last time."
— 'Nagavalokita Vesaliyam Apalokettva'

"This city of Vaishali, well-developed, safe, prosperous, well settled, elegant, palace with beautiful orchards and gardens is competing with the city of deities and angels."

Vaishali Mahotsava

Since 1945, the Vaishali Utsav is celebrated by the Bihar Government on the pious occasion of Mahavir Jayanti every year under the chairmanship of the Governor of Bihar.

In 2013, Chief Minister Shri Nitish Kumar declared that Pavapuri will be connected to Vaishali by constructing a new road.

Dr. Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan (former Vice President) inaugurated the Vaishali Utsava. Former President Ramnath Kovind ji announced the establishment of a Prakrit Language University at Vasokund.

Quotes from Luminaries

"I say to you with conviction that if Lord Mahavir's name is worshipped for any principle today, it is Non-Violence (Ahimsa)."
— Mahatma Gandhi

"He was called 'Jina' meaning victorious. He conquered not kingdoms but his own soul and ego."
— Dr. Radhakrishnan

"Mahavir Swami never broke, he always united."
— Vinoba Bhave

Foundation & Development

A sacred journey — from the first foundation stone in 1956 to the grand Panchkalyanak in 2013

Foundation Stone — 23 April 1956

His Excellency Dr. Rajendra Prasad, the first President of India, laid the foundation stone of 'Bhagwan Mahavir Smarak' at Vasokund, Vaishali.

"Vaishali is the Birthplace of Lord Mahavira. After upheavals of two thousand years, republics have been re-established in India and we get inspiration from this glorious land."

1956
2013

Panchkalyanak Mahotsav — 7–12 December 2013

The grand Panchkalyanak Mahotsav was performed in the benign presence of Elacharya Shri Shrutsagar Ji Muniraj and Muni Shri Saurabh Sagar Ji, with blessings of all Jain Acharyas.

Governors' Visits & Land Grant

The Governors of Bihar — Shri Ramnath Kovind Ji and Shri Satyapal Malik Ji — visited the Birthplace. Shri Malik Ji handed over 2 acres of land for vehicle parking to the Samiti.
